{{Infobox artist | honorific_prefix = | name = William de Alwis Seneviratne | honorific_suffix = | image = A hand-book to the flora of Ceylon (Plate XC) (6430663459).jpg | image_size = 240px | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | birth_name = <!-- only use if different than name --> | birth_date = 1842 | birth_place = | death_date = 1916 | death_place = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} --> | nationality = Sri Lankan | residence = | education = | alma_mater = | known_for = Natural history illustrations | notable_works = | style = | movement = | spouse = | partner = | awards = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) --> | elected = | patrons = | memorials = | website = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} --> | module = }}
'''William de Alwis''' (1842–1916) was a [[Ceylon]]ese [[artist]] and [[entomologist]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pethiyagoda|first=Rohan|date=May 1999|title=The Family de Alwis Seneviratne of Sri Lanka: pioneers in biological illustration|url=http://static1.1.sqspcdn.com/static/f/1199264/18693502/1339431698397/Pethiyagoda+R.+The+Family+de+Alwis+Seneviratne+of+Sri+lanka-+pioneers+in+biological+illustration.pdf?token=UU1kvbI0dn7T8YMa1t3MsCugpHo%3D.|journal=Journal of South Asian Natural History|volume=4|issue=2|pages=99-109|issn=1022-0828|via=}}</ref> With his brother George (dates unknown), William made a lasting contribution to the knowledge of the [[lepidoptera]], (butterflies and moths) of [[Sri Lanka|Ceylon]].
The brothers' father, [[Haramanis de Alwis Seneviratne]] (1792–1894) was a [[botanical illustrator]] who worked at the [[Botanical Gardens]] in Ceylon at [[Kalutara District|Kalutara]] between 1818–1822 and [[Peradeniya]] from 1822–1861.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/170416/plus/the-unknown-de-alwises-brush-with-asian-flora-236894.html|title=The unknown de Alwises’ brush with Asian flora|last=|first=|date=April 16, 2017|website=www.sundaytimes.lk|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=6 January 2018}}</ref> He illustrated over 2,000 plants. William was appointed to succeed him to continue the work as a botanical artist.
[[George Henry Kendrick Thwaites|George Thwaites]], the Director of the [[Royal Botanical Gardens, Peradeniya|Botanical Garden]] at Peradeniya between 1849 and 1879, who was impressed by the de Alwis brothers' botanical drawings, recommended to [[William Henry Gregory|W H Gregory]], the [[Governors of British Ceylon|Governor of Ceylon]], that they should draw from nature the butterflies and moths of Ceylon. Thwaites supervised the drawings, many of which were illustrations of specimens that he had collected himself. The drawings were accurate and later used by a number of authors publishing on the lepidoptera of Ceylon, notably by [[George Morrison Reid Henry]] and [[L G O Woodhouse]]. The De Alwis drawings are in the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]], London.
==Books== * [https://doi.org/10.5962/bhl.title.10864 ''A hand-book to the flora of Ceylon'']. Henry Trimen. London: Dulau, 1893-1931.
